I loved the idea that the mother has a piece and the daughter has a piece, both resembling each other. I hope that when they look at their paintings that they are reminded of each other and the beautiful relationship they have. I hope these paintings serve as a reminder of strength and beauty.

1. Short form video is king (tt and IG are currently fighting for attention, so it’s a golden time to grow. 

2. Get a tripod for your phone and record your creative process to use as footage.

3. Study what other people in your niche are posting, and what is getting views. Emulate that in your own voice.

It can take a bit to find your creative voice, that is ok. Practice makes perfect.

4. posting 3-5 times a week seems to be working well

5. Post each video again on the back end 
When posting a reel, right before you click “share”, toggle off the “also share to feed”. This doesn’t share your video to your followers, but to new people on reels. My theory is it shares your video to an entirely new audience. My first backend post got 3 views and now they get 10k+ so be patient here. 

6.	Use trending songs & experiment with 3-5 hashtags 

Social media is constantly evolving, so remember to play and experiment with new things to see what works best for you. Try not to get discouraged if you don’t get traction at first, persistence is key. The cool thing about social media is I’ve seen people really blow up fast by taking it seriously

A most asked question:
How do I price my art?

The strategy changes when you’re first getting started vs when you are more established. 

When you are getting stated, do this:
Find 10-20 other artists that create art similar to yours. 
You want similar materials, art category, size, artist reputation, etc.. 
For artist reputation, factor in things like years in the industry, social following, art demand, gallery representation, etc. (loose guidelines)

Find how much they charge for their art. Put all this data into a spreadsheet (I use Google Sheets) so you can find the average price people are charging for art similar to yours. Start there. 

Once you start selling and growing in demand, you can start raising your prices to find your sweet spot of supply and demand. Rules can be broken here depending on strategy. 

For example, I’m sold out, my custom art has a 5 month waitlist, & my minis sell out in seconds. This means my demand is much higher than supply, and that I am severely undercharging for my art. 
I am ok with this because I want the price to have a steady and stable increase over my lifetime. 
I also really want to have a collector base of people who really love my art. These people don’t mind the wait and effort it takes to get my art. I’m not saying this strategy is for everyone, but I like it thus far. #howtopriceyourwork #howtopriceart #artadvice

⚠️Clarification!! This is how to use the resin I use. Before using any resin, read instructions and safety requirements as they vary. ⚠️

 My top asked question:
How to paint with resin?

Resin can be difficult to work with, so here are my tips: 

Things you’ll need: 
1. Resin
2. Measuring cup/bucket
3. Mixing sticks 
4. Plastic tarp or cover
5. Propane torch or heat gun 
6. Respirator (optional)
7. Paint (optional)

Make sure you use gloves. A respirator isn’t technically required with this resin, but I prefer to use one for extra safety. Ensure your painting surface is clean, and protect your work area with a tarp. Resin is very sticky, so do your best to work clean. Practice makes perfect here. 

The resin I use is MAS Art Pro 
(use code KIMROSE for 10% off + free shipping) 

The resin is a 1:1 ratio and requires both parts to be mixed thoroughly. Mix equal parts together and stir for 5 minutes, then pour into another container and continue to stir until the 9 minute mark. This ensures it’s fully mixed. If anything isn’t fully mixed, it will never cure and ruin your painting. You can leave clear or add a bit of color to the mix, this is where you can be creative.

At the 10 min mark:
Pour onto the surface and spread. 

At the 35min mark:
Use a torch or heat gun to pop the bubbles. I usually go over every part of the painting twice to ensure all the bubbles add popped. Be thorough and careful to not overheat. 

Scoop out any hair or dust pieces before the 45min mark

For extra protection, cover with a box or create a little tent so dust doesn’t fall on it while it cures. I let sit overnight before moving, and it fully cores in about 11 days. 

My advice is to start small. Be patient with yourself if things don’t always go right. I’ve worked with resin for 5 years and still sometimes have trouble. It’s all part of the creation process :)

Bonus tips: 
1. Experiment with having one gloved “dirty” hand and one non gloved “clean” hand. 
2. Put tape on the back of your painting to make it easier to remove resin drippings
3. Always use a solid surface, wood board canvas works great and is affordable

This is the first art piece I’ve created rooted from the feeling of rage. “Themis”, unveiled at my solo art show Venus’s Garden, is an evolving NFT that shows the inequality of the sexes on a global scale. 

In our current day, where we have made much progress but still lack equality between the sexes, Themis is a display of pink and red inks. If we regress, Themis becomes more red. As we progress, Themis becomes more pink and orange. Once the world reaches 95-100% equality, Themis turns to beautiful waves of gold. The unfortunate reality is that we may never see Themis turn pure gold in our lifetime.

Themis is connected to live data showing objective and measurable benchmarks for global progress toward gender equality. The data is pulled from @worldbank The World Bank’s “Women, Business, and the Law”, which is a database that pulls data from 187 countries and regions of the world. This database is divided into 8 indicators which are: mobility, workplace, pay, marriage, parenthood, entrepreneurship, assets, and pension. Here are just a few of the many indicator subcategories:
- Can a woman open a bank account in the same way as a man? 
- Can a woman choose where to live in the same way as a man? 
- Is the law free of legal provisions that require a married women to obey her husband? 
- Is there legislation specifically addressing domestic violence? 
- Does a woman have the same right to remarry as a man? 
- Is there legislation on sexual harassment in the workplace? 
- Does the law mandate equal remuneration for work of equal value? 
- Do sons and daughters have equal rights to inherit assets from their parents?

I know we have made much progress over the past century, but this is a solid, data driven reminder that there is still work to be done. 

In Greek mythology, Themis is the goddess and personification of justice, divine order, fairness, law, and custom, and her symbols include the Scales of Justice.

One of the best pieces of advice I ever received:

I know this isn’t for everyone, but I know it’s helped me and a lot of other incredible artists 

“If you want to be serious, you need to financially invest in an art studio”

————-

I know this is very targeted advice, but I can say this was exactly what I needed to hear. They said “if you want to be serious about being an artist, you need to financially invest in a studio just for your art”. 

I’ve talked with many other artists, and they agree this was a huge turning point in their career. 

For me, or was the frantic fire under my butt I needed to grow fast. The fear of not being able to stay caused me to push as hard as I possibly could to stay. 

Be smart. Don’t put yourself so financially at risk so that you are so stressed you can’t create.  I saved enough to cover 3 months of bills and a studio I wanted. When moving in, they asked for first month, last month, and security deposit (adding up to 3 months rent). If the studio didn’t make sense after then, I could move out and still cover my normal living expenses. 

I found my studio by checking daily on Craigslist of all places. Craigslist has been amazing for finding deals. Good ones go fast so check daily. 

This is not financial advice, and this isn’t even advice I’d give generally as it isn’t for everyone.  But if it is for you, save up & go for it :) #art #inspiration #motivation

Sirenizar - [Spanish] - meaning to allure or enchant, especially by melodious singing. (SOLD)

When I finally stepped back to look at the finished painting, I heard music 🤍

Sirenizar was designed to have a captivating presence. She is a mixture of contrasting textures, and bright 23k gold set over black stone. My goal was for the piece to be striking from afar, and still allure the viewer to come closer and enjoy all the little details. 

The shape of the painting was inspired by Sandhamn and its surrounding islands. Sandhamn is a small island settlement approximately 50 km east of Stockholm, Sweden. Tranquil, unspoilt, and as close to the natural coastal world as you can get, Sandhamn is one of the furthest islands in the Stockholm archipelago and is a famous Swedish sailing port. Sandhamn has been popular for pleasure boating since the late 19th century, and is one of the most important natural ports in the archipelago with easy access to the Swedish capital. It is known for its tavern, its clubhouse, and its harbour. The painting not only pulls from the shape of the island, but also its charming natural beauty and prestige. 

The deep green was inspired by my love of my piece, Jade. My original Jade painting was inspired by the collector who lives in Taiwan. The jade stone is considered Taiwan's national pride, with many meanings far beyond just a stone. It is believed to eliminate any bad spirits and to bring good luck and fortune to whoever wears it. Jade is more precious than gold, and symbolises prosperity, success, and good luck.

I can’t tell you how many hours I spent on this painting. I lost track, and spent pretty much every waking moment in the studio the last week. I focused only on the art. Nothing else. There’s something beautiful about staying in a constant flow state for so long. Especially late nights for me. But I did learn that to avoid burnout after, moderation is best. 

When I finished, I needed to rush it to the shippers as soon as possible. I was bummed I didn’t schedule a studio shoot, but then I remembered @sophiaschrank . We frequent the same coffee shop a couple of blocks from my studio. We became friends because she is as obsessed with Rhea as I am. Eventually we talked about what we do, and I absolutely adored her photography. 

I DMed her asking if she was available ASAP to come and shoot. She had been traveling in NY, but ✨serendipitously✨ was in LA for a couple of days, and came to my studio to shoot. 

As an artist, I think we can get so in our head. I remember being stressed when Sophia was heading over, wondering “is the painting finished? No. Is the painting finished? No?”. Stress and insecurities flooded my mind. When Sophia walked in and saw the painting for the first time, she said “oh chills, I just got chills. I just need a moment with the painting”. 

A warmth burned in my chest and I smiled. I could’ve cried with how much that meant. 

If there’s a takeaway from this hella long post, it’s 1. Sophia is amazing, and 2. If you see artwork you like, express that to the artist. You don’t realize how much it could mean, even to the most “confident” artists.

Failure is frustrating, financially stressful, and creatively exhausting. But it is also a sign that I am pushing my limits in a fruitful way. 

The most groundbreaking successes have been discovered on the brink of failure. Or even on the other side of failure. For that I must remain grateful for my repeated failures. Anybody can fail, but repeatedly failing, and standing back up even after some pieces are broken, now that takes character.

This is the first art piece I’ve created rooted in the feeling of rage. “Themis”, unveiled at my solo art show Venus’s Garden, is an evolving NFT that shows the inequality of the sexes on a global scale. 

In our current day, where we have made much progress but still lack equality between the sexes, Themis is a display of pink and red inks. If we regress, Themis becomes more red. As we progress, Themis becomes more pink and orange. Once the world reaches 95-100% equality, Themis turns to beautiful waves of gold. The unfortunate reality is that we may never see Themis turn pure gold in our lifetime.

Themis is connected to live data showing objective and measurable benchmarks for global progress toward gender equality. The data is pulled from The World Bank’s “Women, Business, and the Law”, which is a database that pulls data from 187 countries and regions of the world. This database is divided into 8 indicators which are: mobility, workplace, pay, marriage, parenthood, entrepreneurship, assets, and pension. Here are just a few of the many indicator subcategories:

- Can a woman open a bank account in the same way as a man? 
- Can a woman choose where to live in the same way as a man? 
- Is the law free of legal provisions that require married women to obey their husbands? 
- Is there legislation specifically addressing domestic violence? 
- Does a woman have the same right to remarry as a man? 
- Is there legislation on sexual harassment in the workplace? 
- Does the law mandate equal remuneration for work of equal value? 
- Do sons and daughters have equal rights to inherit assets from their parents?

I know we have made much progress over the past century, but this is a solid, data-driven reminder that there is still work to be done. 

In Greek mythology, Themis is the goddess and personification of justice, divine order, fairness, law, and custom, and her symbols include the Scales of Justice.

How to paint with resin:

Materials:
Measuring cups/buckets
Wood mixing sticks
Plastic tarp
Propane torch or heat gun 
Wood board canvas 
Paint (acrylic works great but you can use most anything)
Resin (I use @masepoxies “Art Pro” - use code KIMROSE for 10% off + free shipping)

Step 1: canvas 
Your canvas must be hard, not soft like a cloth canvas. I recommend a wood board canvas, they are affordable and light.

Step 2 : prep 
I use a plastic tarp to cover the space, and plastic cups to prop up the canvas.
Resin doesn’t stick to the plastic so you can reuse these as many times as you’d like.

Prep your cups, sticks, and any paints you’d like to use. You can add paint to the resin for color, or paint with clear resin over an existing piece. I absolutely recommend using small test samples before painting on an actual project. 
For temperature it MUST be 70-80f.

Step 3: Measure
Calculate how much resin you need at this link: 
https://masepoxies.com/resin-calculator/ 
I use 0.98 thickness.

Step 4: Protection
Put on gloves and a respirator. For the gloves, work as clean as possible.
For respirator: use a NIOSH approved respirator. Check get a out my other “tips” video for more respirator tips.
 
Step 5: Paint
Pour 1 part resin and 1 part hardener. 
Hand mix for 5 minutes, then pour into a second separate container and continue to mix to the 9 minute mark. Use a wood stick to pick out any hairs or specks that have landed in the piece.

Step 6: Heat
At the 35 minute mark, use a propane torch or heat gun to pop all the bubbles. If you don’t do it enough, there will be bubbles. If you do it too much, you can burn the resin or cause more bubbles. Practice makes perfect.

Step 7: Cover
I recommend covering the piece, an upside down cardboard box works great for this. There’s lots of other methods you can use to cover which I’ll make a video of in the future.

Let sit for 24hrs before moving & 2 weeks before shipping. Remember to be patient when learning a new skill & practice makes perfect ♥️

Terra, goddess of earth. In ancient Roman mythology, Terra Mater[a] (“Mother Earth”) is the personification of the Earth. Terra is a girl’s name of Latin origin meaning “earth.” The Latin term is used to denote dry land, typically upon return to solid ground after a rough sea voyage.

I fell in love with the Roman and Latin ties to the name, and felt it resonated perfectly with the original technique that inspired the piece. 

—

The gold accent and white stone was first used in my painting, “Jade”. 

Jade, also called “the stone of heaven”, has many meanings far beyond just a stone. It symbolizes prosperity, success, and good luck. It is believed to eliminate any bad spirits and bring good luck and fortune to whoever wears it.

Meanwhile, Kintsugi, meaning “golden joinery”, is a traditional Japanese art form that uses gold to repair broken pottery. This repairs the brokenness in a way that makes the object more beautiful, and even more strong than it was prior to being broken. To me this is a symbol of being broken and coming back stronger and more beautiful than before.

Combining Jade with Kintsugi, I aim to represent healing from brokenness and moving forward with prosperity and success.

The concept behind this piece sparked the theme of my upcoming solo show. Most of my ideas have been written down in my journal. That is where I like to brainstorm and see how I can push creative boundaries. Very few ideas have made my heart race, made me sweat, and this one in particular, made me crawl up into a ball. Lately, the ideas that scare me a bit have been hard to get out of my head. Later journaling what it meant to me, I cried. I still think this piece can make me cry if I sit and think about it too deeply. 

It was a strong reaction, I had to create the piece I wrote about. 

I have always hated blood. (If you made a face reading that don’t worry I made the same face originally, bear with me). Growing up my mom said I had such a steady hand, I should be a surgeon. I would always laugh and know I couldn’t ever consider it because the thought of blood alone makes my skin crawl. But I couldn’t think of anything more precious and life-giving than blood. How it represents life and death all together. How powerful it would be to create with. 

Three of the NFTs in my show were created with a mixture of my blood and poison. The mixture created some of the most beautiful movements I had ever seen. Something I once thought of as horrifying now became mesmerizing. It moved very differently from the paints and inks I’ve used before. It felt more alive. 

As these NFTs age, they get slower and darker. They then go black and die at the end of 100 years. After that, they glow gold for 9 months and then are reborn. We most likely won’t see this part, but our surviving generation will. 

These, as well as many other new NFTs and a few physical pieces, will be on display for my solo show in New York at @elsewhereart_ - they are also available, link in bio to purchase.

New statues now available, link in bio 🖤 I created four new sculptures for the show, some with white gold accents and with 24k gold accents. The concept of the show revolves around the beauty and balance of life and death, which was then translated in the art to ocean blues and blood reds.

The concept of balance shows up in a lot of my work, and for this show the initial concepts were about the balance of life and de*th. Following that I moved to blood and water and their representation and physical needs in life. De*th and has been an uncomfortable topic for me, and I usually have trouble talking about negative things. I’m a very positive person, and like to avoid topics that make people feel sad in any way. When my mom passed, I didn’t like talking about de*th with my friends or bringing it up because of the uncomfortably of it. I don’t like making people feel negative emotions. But lately I’ve become more comfortable with negative feelings, and the part they play in our lives. Negative emotions are part of life. And in some twisted ways that is part of what makes life and our moments on this earth so beautiful. Instead of straying away from things that made me uncomfortable I decided to go head into these concepts.

And on the flip side of that, how de*th is balanced out with life. How sweet life can be and how we can truly go out and live it. I’m fully aware of how cliche this will sound, but I think it’s a timeless topic that needs constant revisiting. We weren’t born to just exist, but I think born to live full and happy lives. How? That’s probably something I’ll spend my entire life discovering. But I think that’s part of the fun. The journey and discoveries we can make if we can taste the sweetness life has to offer us before our chapter on this earth ends. 

The skulls are life size Calaveras, accented with beautiful flowers and details. They felt extremely fitting and encompassing with the feel of the show. A drop of my bl**d may or may not be in the red ones.

When using gold in the studio, I enter a flow state and love how the details come out. 

If there is a takeaway, it’s trust your artistic gut. Art is supposed to be an extension of you as the artist anyway.
